=== Speech ===
Title: Opening Remarks by Mr Ong Ye Kung, Minister for Health, at the Press Conference on Whole-of-Government Efforts to Tackle Vapes
Date: 2025-08-28
Source: Ministry of Health (MOH)
Document Type: Speech / Press Conference
Topic: Vaping, Etomidate, Youth, Whole-of-Government Enforcement, Rehabilitation, Public Health, Nicotine Regulation

Summary:
- Minister Ong Ye Kung outlines the evolving landscape of vaping and substance abuse, highlighting the risks of etomidate-laced vapes.
- Emphasises that vaping has become a gateway to substance abuse, particularly among young people.
- Whole-of-Government (WOG) approach is adopted, involving MOH, MHA, schools, military, and other agencies.
- Etomidate to be listed as Class C drug under the Misuse of Drugs Act (MDA) effective 1 Sep 2025, with transitional measures.
- Enforcement model includes stricter penalties for importers, sellers, traffickers, and escalating penalties for repeat abusers.
- Rehabilitation programmes for first-time etomidate abusers, with community support via QuitVape and agencies like SANA, WeCare, THKMC, Fei Yue.
- General vaping enforcement enhanced, including higher fines for consumption and rehabilitation requirements for recalcitrant vapers.
- Public, media, and social media influencers play key role in awareness campaigns.
- Acknowledgement of MOH and HSA officers for enforcement efforts and public service.

Key Entities:
- Mr Ong Ye Kung (Minister for Health)
- Ministry of Health (MOH)
- Ministry of Home Affairs (MHA)
- Health Sciences Authority (HSA)
- Central Narcotics Bureau (CNB)
- Institutes of Mental Health (IMH)
- Social Service Agencies (SSAs): Singapore Anti-Narcotics Association (SANA), WeCare, Thye Hua Kwan Moral Charities (THKMC), Fei Yue Community Services
- Misuse of Drugs Act (MDA)
- Poisons Act
- Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (TCASA)
- Youth population, under-18 and under-30 age groups
- Media outlets: The Straits Times, social media influencers

Key Concepts:
- Vaping as gateway to substance abuse
- Etomidate-laced vape detection and enforcement
- Whole-of-Government enforcement model
- Class C drug listing under MDA
- Stricter penalties for importers, sellers, traffickers
- Rehabilitation and second-chance programmes
- QuitVape community programme
- Escalation of penalties for repeat offenders
- Nicotine content regulation in e-vaporisers
- Public education and awareness campaigns

Body:
1. Minister opens by describing the changing landscape of vaping and substance abuse.
2. Highlights that vapes now serve as a delivery device for serious substances like etomidate.
3. Notes that young people may start vaping out of curiosity, coercion, or ignorance, potentially leading to substance abuse.
4. Advocates for a Whole-of-Government (WOG) approach to address the issue, involving MOH, MHA, schools, institutes of higher learning, military camps, and public spaces.
5. Announces that etomidate will be listed as a Class C drug under the Misuse of Drugs Act (MDA) effective 1 September 2025.
6. Outlines transitional period goals: encouraging abusers to give up vapes, operational coordination, and legislative review for new enforcement framework.
7. Existing legislation (TCASA, Poisons Act, MDA) will be used until new laws are enacted in early 2026.
8. Enforcement model highlights: tougher penalties for importers, sellers, traffickers; rapid escalation of penalties for abusers.
9. Etomidate abuser profile: mostly young (80% under 30), first-time offenders offered rehabilitation instead of prosecution.
10. Rehabilitation programmes: 3-month programme at IMH and SSAs (SANA, WeCare), weekly reporting, counselling, medical tests, potential extension to 6 months.
11. Repeat offenders subject to arrest under MDA, supervision, or Drug Rehabilitation Centre placement.
12. Community QuitVape programme encourages voluntary cessation without offence records.
13. General vaping enforcement: higher fines ($500â€“$700), rehabilitation programmes for recalcitrant vapers, default penalties up to $2,000 under TCASA.
14. Acknowledges strong public, media, and social media support in raising awareness.
15. Thanks MOH and HSA officers for dedication and bravery in enforcement.

Author:
Mr Ong Ye Kung, Minister for Health
